1. EXECUTIVE SUMMARY

This paper examines the widening gap between Artificial Intelligence Capability (AIC) and Artificial Intelligence Advertising (AIA), hereafter referred to as the Expectation–Reality Liability Gap (ERLG).

While AI systems are probabilistic text and pattern generation tools with known limitations, they are frequently presented in marketing materials using language that implies autonomy, reasoning, understanding, reliability, and professional equivalence. This document does not evaluate the technology itself; rather, it evaluates the representation of the technology and the legal doctrine of Reasonable Reliance (RR) under consumer protection law.

The Institute’s central finding is as follows:

The primary risk in the AI industry is not technological failure, but expectation inflation created by marketing language operating in legally optimized ambiguity space.

In simple terms:
The engineering is probabilistic. The marketing is deterministic. The liability is undecided.

