4. THE AMBIGUITY STRATEGY MODEL

4.1 Legally Optimized Language (LOL)

The Institute has identified a linguistic strategy used in emerging technology sectors called Legally Optimized Language (LOL) — statements that are technically defensible but commonly interpreted in a much stronger way by the public.

Examples include:

Phrase	Public Interpretation	Legal Interpretation
“Can write reports”	Writes accurate reports	Generates text
“Helps with legal work”	Reliable for legal tasks	Produces words about law
“Automates tasks”	Replaces humans	Makes humans supervise faster
“Understands documents”	Comprehends meaning	Detects patterns
“AI agent”	Independent actor	Script with a loop

This communication gap is formally classified as Semantic Liability Drift (SLD).

⸻

5. THE RESPONSIBILITY CHAIN

The Institute rejects the widely used “It’s Just a Tool” Liability Deflection Model (JTL-LDM) when the tool is marketed using capability-implying language.

The legally relevant responsibility chain is:

Party	Responsibility
Company	Must not mislead
Marketing	Must not imply false capability
Legal	Must make ambiguity legally safe
Regulator	Must decide after the damage
Customer	Assumed to be “reasonable”
AI	Cannot be sued (currently very convenient)

This creates what economists call a Liability Vacuum with Revenue Capture (LVRC).

