8. KEY FINDING

The Institute’s primary conclusion is the Expectation–Reality Gap Principle (ERGP):

When a technology is described using human capability language, humans will assume human capability reliability.

This is not a philosophical problem.
This is not a technological problem.
This is a representation problem.

Or more formally:

If you sell a calculator, you are responsible for arithmetic.
If you sell a mind, you are responsible for decisions.

The AI industry is currently attempting to sell something described like a mind, priced like a worker, but legally defined as a calculator.

The Institute predicts this arrangement will continue until a sufficiently expensive court case invents new vocabulary.

